From lawrence.michael at gene.com  Fri Jun 30 15:20:25 2017
From: lawrence.michael at gene.com (Michael Lawrence)
Date: Fri, 30 Jun 2017 06:20:25 -0700
Subject: [Bioc-devel] Help understanding an R performance issue
In-Reply-To: <e5dd0d90-373a-7e5c-755c-7a454634f9d2@igtp.cat>
References: <5b4d6119-d604-38b3-0736-58f80af74443@igtp.cat>
 <CAOQ5NycukLgaJh5QJH2HrMdbt=NtQ=FBgmL3bsX8_M5KsZsDhg@mail.gmail.com>
 <91c1eec9-b96b-ce38-d793-bb2139915ce2@igtp.cat>
 <59561823.1020205@fredhutch.org>
 <e5dd0d90-373a-7e5c-755c-7a454634f9d2@igtp.cat>
Message-ID: <CAOQ5NyffUSOtak5Soi5p6_6YCaQxZV5z74sdEV5ctZB0srbUmA@mail.gmail.com>

The reason it's faster when shuffled vs. all that end is that when a
miss happens R compares the string to all strings before it in the
subscript. So it's a lot worse to have a miss towards the end.

As Martin wrote, there are basically two possible improvements that
are somewhat complementary:
1) Tell stringSubscript() that it is not replacing so there is no need
to do that scan. This would require passing an argument down the call
stack.
2) Do a self match on the subscript like in Martin's patch, although
it should probably be done lazily on the first miss.

Michael

